---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="Design QA Agent">

  <section class="agent-intro">
    <p class="agent-eyebrow">Agent Guide</p>
    <h1 class="agent-h1">Design QA</h1>
    <p class="agent-summary">
      The Design QA agent compares a Figma design frame to a live or staging build and
      produces a structured list of every visual and functional discrepancy. It reads the
      Figma spec via the MCP server, captures the live page at the correct matching viewport,
      then works through layout, spacing, typography, colour, and interactive elements — verifying
      that clicks produce actual DOM changes, not just that the cursor landed in the right place.
      Use it after engineering delivers a new feature to confirm the build matches the spec before
      going to production.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Setup callout ─────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <a href="/getting-started" class="setup-callout">
    <span class="setup-callout-icon">⚙</span>
    <div>
      <p class="setup-callout-title">First time? Complete the setup guide first</p>
      <p class="setup-callout-sub">You'll need GitHub Desktop, the Claude Code desktop app, the Chrome extension, and the agent skills installed before any agent will work. →</p>
    </div>
  </a>

  <!-- ── Connecting Figma MCP ───────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Connecting Figma to Claude Desktop</h2>
    <p class="guide-body">
      The Design QA agent reads design specs directly from Figma using the Figma MCP server.
      This is a one-time setup — once connected, it persists across all Claude Code sessions.
    </p>

    <div class="figma-steps">

      <div class="figma-step">
        <span class="figma-step-num">1</span>
        <div>
          <p class="figma-step-title">Install the Figma plugin</p>
          <p class="figma-step-body">
            Open Claude Desktop and start a Claude Code session with the repo open. In the
            Claude Code prompt, run:
          </p>
          <pre class="code-block">claude plugin install figma@claude-plugins-official</pre>
          <p class="figma-step-body">Press Enter and wait for the installation to complete.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="figma-step">
        <span class="figma-step-num">2</span>
        <div>
          <p class="figma-step-title">Restart Claude Desktop</p>
          <p class="figma-step-body">
            Quit the app completely and reopen it. Plugins are loaded at startup.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="figma-step">
        <span class="figma-step-num">3</span>
        <div>
          <p class="figma-step-title">Authenticate with Figma</p>
          <p class="figma-step-body">
            In the Claude Code prompt, type <code>/plugin</code> and press Enter. Use the
            arrow keys to navigate to the <strong>Installed</strong> tab, select
            <strong>figma</strong>, and press Enter. Press Enter again to begin
            authentication — a browser tab will open asking you to allow access. Click
            <strong>Allow access</strong>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="figma-step">
        <span class="figma-step-num">4</span>
        <div>
          <p class="figma-step-title">Confirm it's connected</p>
          <p class="figma-step-body">
            Run <code>/plugin</code> again — the Figma server should now show as connected.
            You're ready to use the Design QA agent.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>

    <div class="figma-note">
      <strong>Already have the Figma desktop app?</strong>
      There's also a desktop server option that connects directly through the Figma app
      instead of via a plugin. It's mainly for organisation and enterprise setups — for most
      users, the plugin route above is simpler and recommended.
    </div>

  </section>

  <!-- ── Before you start ────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Before you start</h2>
    <ul class="checklist">
      <li>The Figma URL for the design frame you want QA'd — link to a specific frame with a <code>node-id</code>, not the root file</li>
      <li>The live or staging URL of the built page</li>
      <li>Figma MCP is connected in your Claude Code session (see setup above)</li>
      <li>Confirm which viewport(s) to check. If you don't specify, the agent will match the Figma frame's <code>original_width</code> exactly — it never assumes desktop for a mobile frame</li>
      <li>If the build is on a staging URL behind a VPN or basic auth, confirm it's reachable from your machine before starting</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- ── How to trigger ──────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">How to trigger it</h2>
    <p class="guide-body">Use the slash command directly, or describe the comparison in plain English — include both the Figma URL and the live URL in the same message:</p>
    <div class="trigger-block">
      <code class="trigger-command">/design-qa</code>
    </div>
    <div class="trigger-examples">
      <span class="trigger-chip">"QA this — [Figma URL] vs [live URL]"</span>
      <span class="trigger-chip">"does the build match the design?"</span>
      <span class="trigger-chip">"compare figma to the live page"</span>
      <span class="trigger-chip">"did the engineer get this right?"</span>
    </div>
    <p class="guide-body guide-body--tip">The more specific the Figma link, the more accurate the QA. Link to the exact frame being reviewed rather than the whole file or a parent page.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Step-by-step walkthrough ───────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Step-by-step walkthrough</h2>
    <ol class="steps">
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">1</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Figma design is read</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            The agent calls <code>get_screenshot</code> on the Figma URL to capture the design
            frame, and reads the <code>original_width</code> from the response — this is the
            frame's true canvas width and determines the viewport to use on the live page.
            It also calls <code>get_design_context</code> to extract the exact spacing, padding,
            typography, and colour values from the spec.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">2</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Viewport is matched to the Figma frame</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            The live page is always tested at the same width as the Figma frame — never assumed
            to be desktop. Frames ≤430px wide use a 390px viewport; frames >768px use 1440px.
            This matters: padding errors, layout breaks, and scroll container issues are only
            visible at the correct size.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">3</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Live page is captured</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            The agent navigates to the live URL at the correct viewport, waits for full load
            including skeleton states and lazy-loaded images, then takes a full-page screenshot
            for side-by-side comparison with the Figma frame.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">4</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Visual comparison — every category</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            Working through the design systematically: <strong>layout and structure</strong>
            (proportions, missing/extra sections); <strong>spacing and padding</strong> — checked
            carefully against the Figma spec values, especially on mobile where a few extra px
            of horizontal padding removes significant content width;
            <strong>horizontal scroll containers</strong> — elements clipped at the Figma frame
            edge signal scroll-reveal intent, and side margins preventing full-bleed on the live
            page are a bug; <strong>typography</strong> (family, size, weight, colour, letter
            spacing); and <strong>colour and visual style</strong> (backgrounds, borders, radius,
            shadows). The agent also checks that data elements show the correct <em>type</em> of
            content — benefit icons vs nutrition macros look similar but communicate entirely
            different things.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">5</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Interaction testing — outcomes verified, not just clicks</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            For every interactive element the agent verifies the expected DOM change happened
            after the click — a click that registers but changes nothing is a Fail. Tabs pass
            only when: (1) the clicked tab gains its active state, (2) the previously active
            tab loses its active state, and (3) the content area updates. The agent tests
            product type tabs, filter tabs, dropdowns, accordions, image galleries, subscription
            toggles, and ATC buttons. Anchor links (<code>href="#section"</code>) are flagged
            for manual verification — automated clicks don't reliably trigger native anchor
            scroll in extension-controlled tabs.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">6</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">QA report is written</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            The output is a structured markdown report with two tables: a <strong>visual
            discrepancies table</strong> (location, design spec, live implementation, severity)
            and an <strong>interaction test results table</strong> (element, expected, actual,
            status: ✅ Pass / ❌ Fail / ⚠️ Verify manually). The report ends with an overall
            status — 🟢 Approved, 🟡 Approved with minor fixes, or 🔴 Needs rework — and a
            short priority list for the engineer.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Output format ──────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Output format</h2>
    <p class="guide-body">The Design QA report is output as a structured markdown document in chat — it is not committed to the repo as an Astro page. Copy it into a Notion doc, Jira ticket, or Slack message for the engineer. The format is:</p>
    <ul class="file-list">
      <li>Header — page/frame name, Figma URL, live URL, Figma frame width, viewport tested, date</li>
      <li>Visual discrepancies table — location, design spec, live implementation, severity (High / Medium / Low)</li>
      <li>Interaction test results table — element, expected, actual, status</li>
      <li>Summary — total counts, overall status, top priorities</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Tips and common issues ────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Tips and common issues</h2>
    <ul class="tips-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Always link to a specific Figma frame, not the file root.</strong>
        The agent reads <code>original_width</code> from the frame to set the correct viewport.
        Without a specific frame URL the agent cannot determine the right size, and the entire
        comparison will be at the wrong scale.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Anchor links need manual verification.</strong>
        Clicking a <code>href="#section"</code> link via automation does not reliably trigger
        native browser scroll in extension-controlled tabs. The agent marks these as
        "⚠️ Verify manually" — test them yourself in a regular browser tab.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Price and review count differences are usually dynamic content.</strong>
        A £39.99 in Figma vs £37.99 on the live page is not a design discrepancy — prices
        change. These are flagged as Low severity rather than bugs.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Extra elements not in the spec.</strong>
        New badges, additional tabs, or extra content added since the design was created are
        flagged but not automatically failed — they may be intentional additions. The agent
        notes them and asks you to confirm.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Horizontal scroll containers are full-bleed by design.</strong>
        If the Figma shows a tab label or card clipped at the screen edge, that's intentional
        scroll-reveal design. Side margins on the live container that prevent full-bleed are a
        bug — flag them as Medium or High depending on how broken the scroll feels.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style>
  .setup-callout {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: 14px;
    background: #EEF6F7;
    border: 1px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.18);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--color-primary);
    border-radius: 0 10px 10px 0;
    padding: 16px 20px;
    margin-bottom: 40px;
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: background 0.15s;
    max-width: 680px;
  }
  .setup-callout:hover { background: #E4F0F2; }
  .setup-callout-icon { font-size: 18px; color: var(--color-primary); opacity: 0.6; flex-shrink: 0; margin-top: 1px; }
  .setup-callout-title { font-size: 14px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 4px; }
  .setup-callout-sub { font-size: 13px; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--color-text-body); }

  .agent-intro { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .agent-eyebrow {
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    color: var(--color-primary);
    opacity: 0.5;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  .agent-h1 {
    font-size: clamp(26px, 4vw, 38px);
    font-weight: 800;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    line-height: 1.15;
  }
  .agent-summary {
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    max-width: 680px;
  }

  .guide-section { margin-bottom: 52px; }
  .section-heading {
    font-size: 20px;
    font-weight: 800;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    padding-bottom: 10px;
    border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0,57,66,0.08);
  }
  .sub-heading {
    font-size: 14px;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin: 20px 0 8px;
  }

  .guide-body {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .guide-body--tip {
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-mint);
    padding: 10px 14px;
    border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0;
    margin-top: 12px;
  }

  .checklist {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
  }
  .checklist li {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    padding-left: 22px;
    position: relative;
  }
  .checklist li::before {
    content: '→';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-primary);
    opacity: 0.4;
    font-size: 13px;
  }

  .trigger-block { margin-bottom: 16px; }
  .trigger-command {
    display: inline-block;
    font-size: 15px;
    font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
    background: var(--color-primary);
    color: var(--color-mint);
    padding: 8px 18px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.01em;
  }
  .trigger-examples {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 8px;
    margin-bottom: 14px;
  }
  .trigger-chip {
    font-size: 13px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    border: var(--card-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-chip);
    padding: 5px 12px;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  code {
    font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
    font-size: 12.5px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    color: var(--color-primary);
    padding: 2px 6px;
    border-radius: 4px;
  }

  .code-block {
    font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
    font-size: 13px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    padding: 16px 20px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    line-height: 1.7;
    overflow-x: auto;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    border: var(--card-border);
    white-space: pre;
  }

  .file-list {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 6px;
    margin-bottom: 4px;
  }
  .file-list li {
    font-size: 14px;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    padding-left: 16px;
    position: relative;
  }
  .file-list li::before {
    content: '·';
    position: absolute;
    left: 4px;
    color: var(--color-primary);
    opacity: 0.4;
  }

  .steps { list-style: none; display: flex; flex-direction: column; }
  .step {
    display: flex;
    gap: 20px;
    align-items: flex-start;
    padding: 24px 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(0,57,66,0.08);
  }
  .step:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .step-number {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 34px;
    height: 34px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--color-primary);
    color: var(--color-mint);
    font-size: 13px;
    font-weight: 800;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    margin-top: 2px;
  }
  .step-title {
    font-size: 15px;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }
  .step-desc {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
  }

  .figma-steps {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0;
    max-width: 680px;
    border: var(--card-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-card);
    overflow: hidden;
    background: var(--color-bg-card);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .figma-step {
    display: flex;
    gap: 16px;
    align-items: flex-start;
    padding: 18px 20px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(0,57,66,0.07);
  }
  .figma-step:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .figma-step-num {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 28px;
    height: 28px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--color-primary);
    color: var(--color-mint);
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 800;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    margin-top: 2px;
  }
  .figma-step-title {
    font-size: 14px;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 5px;
  }
  .figma-step-body {
    font-size: 13.5px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }
  .figma-step-body:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
  .figma-note {
    max-width: 680px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    border: var(--card-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-card);
    padding: 13px 16px;
    font-size: 13.5px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
  }
  .figma-note strong {
    display: block;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 3px;
  }

  .tips-list {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 16px;
  }
  .tips-list li {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    background: var(--color-bg-card);
    border: var(--card-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-card);
    padding: 16px 18px;
  }
  .tips-list strong {
    display: block;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 4px;
  }
</style>
